Four days after he examined ,the materiale which Bishop William had prepared for the erection of the bridge over the Dee He found also the buildings in the neighbourhood of the College which he had begun still incomplete. A strong desire seized him to build the bridge aud complete Bishop Elphinstone's other works. For the better execution of these designs he wished Alexander Galloway (mentioned before), to whom as his chief and most faithful friend Bishop William had entrusted all his fortunes, to take charge of the bishop's legacies and employ thern in the way destined in his will. For he in Elphinstone's lifetime had above all others favoured the College and done much for its advantage. He was therefore in · the opinion of all the man best suited for this taslr.
